  "prompt": "I'm a US citizen and my boyfriend is Argentinean; if we get married in the US, how long will it take for him to be qualified to work in the US?",
  "response": "Marrying a U.S. citizen provides a pathway for your Argentinean spouse to obtain lawful permanent residency (a Green Card) in the United States, which includes the authorization to work. Here's an overview of the typical process and associated timelines:\n\n### 1. **Marriage in the U.S.**\n   - **Valid Marriage:** Ensure that your marriage is legally recognized in the state where it takes place. This is a foundational step for any immigration benefits to follow.\n\n### 2. **Adjusting Status (If Already in the U.S.)**\n   - **Form I-130 & I-485:** As a U.S. citizen, you would file a **Form I-130 (Petition for Alien Relative)** and your spouse would file a **Form I-485 (Application to Register Permanent Residence or Adjust Status)** concurrently.\n   - **Processing Time:** Typically, the entire process takes **10 to 13 months**, but this can vary based on USCIS workload and specific case circumstances.\n\n### 3. **Employment Authorization**\n   - **Form I-765:** When filing the Form I-485, your spouse can also submit a **Form I-765 (Application for Employment Authorization)**.\n   - **EAD Approval:** After submitting Form I-765, it generally takes about **5 to 7 months** to receive the Employment Authorization Document (EAD), allowing your spouse to work legally in the U.S. while the Green Card application is pending.\n\n### 4. **Consular Processing (If Abroad)**\n   - If your spouse is residing outside the U.S., you would go through **consular processing**, which involves submitting the I-130 from abroad and attending an interview at a U.S. embassy or consulate.\n   - **Processing Time:** This route can take **12 to 18 months** or longer, depending on various factors like embassy workload and security clearances.\n\n### 5. **After Approval**\n   - Once the Green Card is approved, your spouse will have the right to live and work permanently in the U.S.\n   - **Conditional Residency:** If the marriage is less than two years old at the time of Green Card approval, your spouse will receive a conditional Green Card valid for two years. You'll need to later file to remove these conditions.\n\n### **Important Considerations**\n- **Documentation:** Ensure all forms are filled out accurately and submitted with the required supporting documents to avoid delays.\n- **Biometrics and Interviews:** Your spouse may need to attend a biometrics appointment and an interview as part of the application process.\n- **Legal Assistance:** Immigration laws can be complex. It's often beneficial to consult with an experienced immigration attorney to navigate the process smoothly and address any unique circumstances.\n\n### **Current Processing Times**\n- **USCIS Website:** Processing times can change frequently. For the most up-to-date information, check the [USCIS Processing Times](https://egov.uscis.gov/processing-times/) webpage and select the form and service center relevant to your case.\n\n### **Conclusion**\nWhile the process can take several months to over a year, obtaining the Employment Authorization Document (EAD) typically becomes possible within the first half-year after filing, allowing your spouse to work in the U.S. while awaiting final approval for permanent residency.\n\n**Disclaimer:** This information is intended for general informational purposes and should not be construed as legal advice. For personalized assistance, please consult with a qualified immigration attorney or accredited representative.",
